Fix CI build by requiring a newer Emacs

In a commit made by @tarsius a few months ago, this code started using
`dolist-with-progress-reporter`, which wasn't added until Emacs
27.1. The CI build has been broken since then on Emacs 26.x.

I guess it's acceptable to start requiring Emacs 27 to fix this.

commit.message:
package-build--cleanup: Work around mercurial's broken purge command

I tried using these arguments:

  --all                  purge ignored files too
  -y --noninteractive    do not prompt, automatically pick the
                         first choice for all prompts

But sadly that does not work as advertised:

  $ hg purge --all -y
  permanently delete 1 ignored files? (yN) n
  abort: removal cancelled

  $ hg -y purge --all
  permanently delete 1 ignored files? (yN) n
  abort: removal cancelled

  $ hg purge --all --noninteractive
  permanently delete 1 ignored files? (yN) n
  abort: removal cancelled

Additionally there is no argument to include "unknown" files, i.e.,
files that are neither tracked nor ignored.  No such files should
exist in our case, because no human touches these repositories, but
they do.  So it appears that when one checks out a new revision that
lacks some files that the previously checked out revision had, these
files are left in the worktree.

So we have no choice but to manually clean out the ignored and unknown
files, and then run the purge command anyway, in case there happen to
be other files that have to be purged; and hope that it will comply
and remove those.

verification.payload:
tree 070e57e610915dd6ca7d980d8375e6e7b1507437
parent 0081876d33d50eadd0f705863a5ae68a62684e32
author Jonas Bernoulli <jonas@bernoul.li> 1692550238 +0200
committer Jonas Bernoulli <jonas@bernoul.li> 1692550238 +0200

commit.message:
Noninteractively collect log of errors

The new file is named "errors.log" and is located in
`package-build-archive-dir'.  It only records the date, the name of
the package, and the oneline error message.  More detailed information
continues to be logged to "<package>.log" in the same directory.

commit.message:
No longer always signal an error if no version can be detected

On the "unstable" channel (and the upcoming "snapshot" channel) we
should always be able to come up with a version number, regardless of
whether upstream does releases.  If we fail to do so, then that might
be due to a bug in our code, or due to an upstream defect, and an
error is appropriate in either case.

On the "stable" channel we only publish packages whose upstreams tag
releases.  If they don't do that in a way we can detect, then that is
unfortunate but not necessarily a bug.  Don't signal an error in this
case, to avoid a very large number of false-positives.

On the upcoming "release" channel, we fall back to publishing the
same snapshot version as on the "snapshot" channel, when we cannot
determine the upstream release.  If we fail to either detect the
upstream release or else fall back to the snapshot version, then
that likely is a bug in our code, so an error is appropriate.

commit.message:
package-build--insert-version-header-log(git): No longer follow renames

If a release a tag before a package is renamed but no new tag is
created after the rename, then building a tarball for the latest
release would fail, because the library matching the (new) package
name would be missing in the tagged release.
